<i>This task is merely a warm-up exercise.</i>

292
00:15:20,310 --> 00:15:24,690
<i>Any chef who's daunted by something
 like this isn't needed at Tohtsuki.</i>

293
00:15:25,860 --> 00:15:29,150
We need to finish fishing ASAP and get cooking!

294
00:15:29,150 --> 00:15:31,200
What should we cook, Souma-kun?

295
00:15:31,200 --> 00:15:33,530
If we get char or rainbow trout, maybe we can grill it with salt?

296
00:15:33,530 --> 00:15:35,160
Or maybe braise it?

297
00:15:35,160 --> 00:15:37,000
We have to think of the accompaniments too!

298
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:39,580
Maybe there are mountain
 vegetables or something!

299
00:15:39,580 --> 00:15:43,760
But everyone else will be thinking 
the same way, y'know?

300
00:15:43,760 --> 00:15:46,090
I want to go for a bit of a twist.

301
00:15:46,090 --> 00:15:48,670
We don't have time for that!

302
00:15:48,670 --> 00:15:51,090
We have to finish our dish!

303
00:15:51,090 --> 00:15:52,840
Sure, but...

304
00:15:56,720 --> 00:15:58,060
You caught it!

305
00:15:58,560 --> 00:15:59,810
Yay!

306
00:16:00,090 --> 00:16:02,230
We managed to get the fish, at least.

307
00:16:02,230 --> 00:16:03,310
Yup.

308
00:16:03,310 --> 00:16:06,020
We just have to figure out how to prepare 'em.

309
00:16:08,400 --> 00:16:10,030
Please use your rigorous judgment!

310
00:16:10,030 --> 00:16:10,620
Shut up!

311
00:16:10,620 --> 00:16:11,530
Shut up, okay?

312
00:16:12,740 --> 00:16:14,410
You guys are using fish too?

313
00:16:16,030 --> 00:16:18,330
This is ridiculous.

314
00:16:18,330 --> 00:16:21,310
Everyone's going with fish because of the theme.

315
00:16:21,310 --> 00:16:23,620
Isn't that awfully narrow-minded?

316
00:16:24,750 --> 00:16:26,790
Get off your high horse.

317
00:16:26,790 --> 00:16:28,710
You got something better?

318
00:16:29,710 --> 00:16:30,550
Can't you tell?

319
00:16:31,590 --> 00:16:32,380
It's duck!

320
00:16:33,090 --> 00:16:35,220
What?! Duck?!

321
00:16:35,220 --> 00:16:36,600
We didn't just find duck.

322
00:16:36,600 --> 00:16:39,010
There were chickens and rabbits too.

323
00:16:39,260 --> 00:16:42,140
We were wondering why
 no one else was around.

324
00:16:43,100 --> 00:16:43,940
Damn it!

325
00:16:43,940 --> 00:16:46,310
I had no idea there were 
ingredients other than river fish.

326
00:16:46,310 --> 00:16:48,730
But it's not like we've ever 
dressed that kind of meat.

327
00:16:48,730 --> 00:16:50,440
Out of my way.

328
00:16:50,440 --> 00:16:52,070
Step aside, Yukihira.

329
00:16:56,370 --> 00:16:57,070
Isami!

330
00:16:57,070 --> 00:16:57,950
Okay!

331
00:17:03,370 --> 00:17:07,290
<i>He's separating the breast and
 thigh meat with such precision.</i>

332
00:17:07,290 --> 00:17:08,710
<i>But despite that speed,</i>

333
00:17:08,710 --> 00:17:10,630
<i>he's not damaging the innards at all.</i>

334
00:17:11,300 --> 00:17:13,130
<i>What agile knife work.</i>

335
00:17:14,130 --> 00:17:15,840
Yes? Did you want to ask me something?

336
00:17:15,840 --> 00:17:18,600
N-No, I was just admiring your skills.

337
00:17:18,600 --> 00:17:19,890
Really?

338
00:17:19,890 --> 00:17:23,560
But my brother can finish this 
three times faster than me.

339
00:17:30,270 --> 00:17:32,990
<i>There's no break in the work flow between any steps.</i>

340
00:17:33,740 --> 00:17:36,820
<i>His moves are smooth and efficient.</i>

341
00:17:37,160 --> 00:17:38,820
<i>Just who </i>is<i> he?</i>

342
00:17:38,820 --> 00:17:42,040
Well, I had no doubt that he'd be at least this good.

343
00:17:42,540 --> 00:17:45,540
He has hands that look like
they'd been tested in an actual kitchen.

344
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:48,920
Forno accendere.

345
00:17:52,420 --> 00:17:54,170
Forgive my belated introduction.

346
00:17:54,170 --> 00:17:56,470
My name is Takumi Aldini.

347
00:17:57,510 --> 00:17:59,800
This is my younger twin.

348
00:17:59,800 --> 00:18:01,850
Isami Aldini.

349
00:18:02,510 --> 00:18:06,180
We previously worked in 
our family's trattoria in Italy.

350
00:18:06,180 --> 00:18:07,310
"Trattoria"?

351
00:18:07,560 --> 00:18:11,520
In Italian, it means a restaurant for the masses.

352
00:18:12,780 --> 00:18:14,860
I'm the same as you, Yukihira.

353
00:18:15,360 --> 00:18:19,320
I too am a chef who's been protecting his restaurant on the front lines.

354
00:18:19,980 --> 00:18:22,240
I remember what you said 
at the opening ceremony.

355
00:18:22,740 --> 00:18:26,250
<i>I don't plan on losing to folks
who've never served a single customer.</i>

356
00:18:26,510 --> 00:18:29,330
You identified yourself as a professional.

357
00:18:29,330 --> 00:18:32,460
As a fellow professional, I cannot lose to you.

358
00:18:32,730 --> 00:18:36,670
Let's show the world who's the better chef, Aldini or Yukihira!

359
00:18:37,390 --> 00:18:38,590
Great!

360
00:18:39,340 --> 00:18:40,390
Come at me!

361
00:18:40,390 --> 00:18:41,140
What?!

362
00:18:42,890 --> 00:18:43,470
Very well.

363
00:18:44,680 --> 00:18:46,310
What's that?!

364
00:18:47,430 --> 00:18:48,980
<i>A mezzaluna.</i>

365
00:18:48,980 --> 00:18:53,400
<i>A double-handed knife used in Italy whose name means "half-moon."</i>

366
00:18:53,770 --> 00:18:54,400
Let's go!

367
00:18:54,900 --> 00:18:56,190
Tritare!

368
00:18:57,610 --> 00:19:00,530
He has complete mastery over that strange knife!

369
00:19:00,530 --> 00:19:03,240
The ingredients are rapidly turning into a paste!

370
00:19:03,520 --> 00:19:05,330
The duck's almost done.

371
00:19:05,330 --> 00:19:06,950
We'll finish the salsa at the same time.

372
00:19:06,950 --> 00:19:07,950
Got it.

373
00:19:07,950 --> 00:19:09,330
I'm ready.

374
00:19:09,330 --> 00:19:10,580
All right!

375
00:19:15,710 --> 00:19:16,710
What?!

376
00:19:25,010 --> 00:19:26,100
Tre...

377
00:19:27,520 --> 00:19:28,560
Due...

378
00:19:30,060 --> 00:19:31,020
Uno...

379
00:19:32,650 --> 00:19:33,730
Fine!

380
00:19:36,910 --> 00:19:38,280
You're the first to finish!

381
00:19:38,590 --> 00:19:42,200
Nimbleness is one of Italian
 cuisine's charms, after all.

382
00:19:42,570 --> 00:19:43,780
<i>They're way too fast!</i>

383
00:19:43,780 --> 00:19:45,830
<i>They had to dress the duck too!</i>

384
00:19:45,830 --> 00:19:47,660
<i>I can't believe they didn't even take an hour!</i>

385
00:19:48,060 --> 00:19:50,000
Grilled duck with herbs

386
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:52,370
and a green sauce.

387
00:19:52,870 --> 00:19:54,250
Buon appetito!

388
00:19:55,540 --> 00:19:56,460
Well then,

389
00:19:57,030 --> 00:19:58,460
I'll have a taste.

390
00:20:02,380 --> 00:20:09,720
<i>The fragrant, wild flavor of the duck 
is heightened by the astringent sauce!</i>

391
00:20:13,770 --> 00:20:18,900
<i>The masculinity and class of this dish is like a heavy bass resounding in the recesses of my stomach.</i>

392
00:20:18,900 --> 00:20:20,150
<i>It is as if...</i>

393
00:20:25,800 --> 00:20:28,260
<i>the duck were singing an aria.</i>

394
00:20:32,210 --> 00:20:34,040
<i>I wouldn't mind being embraced</i>

395
00:20:34,040 --> 00:20:35,420
<i>by a duck like this!</i>

396
00:20:39,250 --> 00:20:39,960
Hey!

397
00:20:39,960 --> 00:20:41,450
That green sauce.

398
00:20:41,450 --> 00:20:43,340
Isn't it salsa verde?

399
00:20:43,340 --> 00:20:48,970
Isn't that a staple in Italian cuisine, made from chopped anchovies and flat-leaf parsley?

400
00:20:49,260 --> 00:20:50,560
What are they thinking?!

401
00:20:50,560 --> 00:20:52,270
The theme's Japanese cuisine!

402
00:20:52,270 --> 00:20:54,440
They're gonna get failed for sure!

403
00:20:54,440 --> 00:20:58,770
No, this sauce was not prepared with anchovies

404
00:20:58,770 --> 00:21:01,070
but with uruka, salted sweetfish offal.

405
00:21:02,220 --> 00:21:06,360
Uruka is traditionally made over the course of a week or more,

406
00:21:06,360 --> 00:21:08,240
but this one is instant, isn't it?

407
00:21:08,240 --> 00:21:08,870
Yes.

408
00:21:09,200 --> 00:21:12,000
We boiled the rinsed sweetfish guts in sake,

409
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:14,620
then seasoned it with mirin, soy sauce, and salt.

410
00:21:14,620 --> 00:21:16,420
We were able to quickly make a rich uruka,

411
00:21:16,420 --> 00:21:18,840
with just the right amount of bitterness.

412
00:21:19,170 --> 00:21:20,380
How is that possible?

413
00:21:20,380 --> 00:21:22,300
That wasn't their only ingenious idea.

414
00:21:23,260 --> 00:21:26,130
Instead of parsley, they chopped perilla and chives,

415
00:21:26,130 --> 00:21:30,810
producing the vibrant green
 color and astringent flavor.

416
00:21:30,810 --> 00:21:34,980
They also subbed in yuzu pepper
 paste instead of garlic,

417
00:21:34,980 --> 00:21:36,940
which is rarely used in Japanese cuisine,

418
00:21:36,940 --> 00:21:39,270
in order to bring the dish closer to the theme.

419
00:21:39,270 --> 00:21:40,570
That's right!

420
00:21:40,570 --> 00:21:42,860
This is Japanese-style salsa verde,

421
00:21:42,860 --> 00:21:44,530
using instant uruka as the base!

422
00:21:44,900 --> 00:21:47,530
They created a Japanese version of an Italian sauce?

423
00:21:47,530 --> 00:21:48,200
Damn it!

424
00:21:48,200 --> 00:21:50,330
I'm getting hungry just listening to them talk.

425
00:21:50,330 --> 00:21:55,210
How'd they manage to combine that many ingredients out here in the mountains?

426
00:21:55,830 --> 00:21:57,830
<i>Unlike Japan,</i>

427
00:21:57,830 --> 00:22:01,460
<i>Italy has a long tradition of meat-based cuisine.</i>

428
00:22:01,460 --> 00:22:03,760
<i>In their homeland of Tuscany,</i>

429
00:22:03,760 --> 00:22:08,510
<i>meats such as duck, rabbit, and boar are served when in season.</i>

430
00:22:08,510 --> 00:22:13,520
<i>They must've learned how to
 dress duck while living there.</i>

431
00:22:14,020 --> 00:22:18,780
<i>The breast has been basted with a sauce made from soy sauce, mustard, black pepper, and honey,</i>

432
00:22:18,780 --> 00:22:20,360
<i>then grilled to aromatic perfection.</i>

433
00:22:20,360 --> 00:22:22,520
<i>It pairs well with the sauce.</i>

434
00:22:23,230 --> 00:22:27,450
You've introduced core elements of Japanese cuisine into both the duck and the salsa verde,

435
00:22:28,050 --> 00:22:30,910
and you've pulled it all together into an exquisite Japanese dish.

436
00:22:31,360 --> 00:22:33,830
Takumi Aldini and Isami Aldini,

437
00:22:34,330 --> 00:22:35,830
you have passed my test.

438
00:22:35,830 --> 00:22:37,080
Grazie!

439
00:22:37,370 --> 00:22:40,830
<i>He used his wits to create an exceptional dish,</i>

440
00:22:41,150 --> 00:22:43,960
<i>despite the limitations imposed upon us.</i>

441
00:22:43,960 --> 00:22:45,340
<i>He reminds me...</i>

442
00:22:46,210 --> 00:22:47,760
<i>of Souma-kun.</i>

443
00:24:26,400 --> 00:24:30,860
Ah! Merveilleuse!

444
00:24:31,240 --> 00:24:33,860
Nakiri Erina, you have passed my test!

445
00:24:35,150 --> 00:24:36,580
Good day.

446
00:24:40,600 --> 00:24:42,710
Next time on <i>Shokugeki no Souma</i>,

447
00:24:43,080 --> 00:24:44,250
the ninth dish:

448
00:24:46,330 --> 00:24:48,240
The Batter to Adorn the Mountains.

449
00:24:49,500 --> 00:24:50,540
Grazie!

450
00:24:50,540 --> 00:24:51,590
Grazie.

